<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910515-0039</DOCNO><DOCID>910515-0039.</DOCID><HL>   Lawsuit Charges Unit   Of McDonnell Douglas   Faked Helicopter Tests</HL><DATE>05/15/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   MD</CO><MS>TECHNOLOGY (TEC)</MS><IN>AEROSPACE (ARO)</IN><GV>DEFENSE DEPARTMENT (DEF)JUSTICE DEPARTMENT (JUS)</GV><RE>MISSOURI (MO)</RE><LP>   LOS ANGELES -- A former test engineer for McDonnellDouglas Helicopter Co. claims the company faked test resultsto cover up faults in the communications system of the Army'sApache helicopter, according to a lawsuit unsealed in federalcourt here.   The whistleblower suit was filed two years ago under theFederal False Claims Act by Jerome Butler, the formeremployee, but kept under seal to allow governmentinvestigators time to look into the charges. The Departmentof Justice opted not to join in the case, said Mr. Butler'sattorney, Herbert Hafif.</LP><TEXT>   Mr. Hafif said Mr. Butler decided to pursue the case inpart because his son is an Apache pilot. The attorney addedthat damages in the case could range between $20 million and$50 million. Spokesmen for McDonnell Douglas Helicopter, aunit of McDonnell Douglas Corp., based in St. Louis, couldn'tbe reached for comment.</TEXT></DOC>